@NilsMelzer said- "Whatever legal system you apply, it gravely violates human rights to publicly portray #Assange as a rape suspect for 9yrs without formal indictment despite questioning him twice & having full access to all evidence, none of which supports the State’s suspicion.

They were not pressing charges; their inquiry to police was about STD testing.  
From this visit to a police station to make an inquiry, 
a person's character has been assassinated over and over again, fusing his name with the word rape when it simply didn't occur.

Both women had consensual sex with Assange — 
quite a lot of it apparently. 
Neither claims they said no or showed or demonstrated non-consent. 
One of the women stated that she felt “railroaded” by police and refused to sign her statement.

Everyone I know who has done the same has reached the same conclusion. 
But regardless of my opinion, 
Julian has rights, 
which are being trampled on systematically, 
and among those rights are the right to be presumed innocent.
A Swedish court has since rejected the prosecutor’s request for his detention as it was disproportionate. I have looked into the case, read the documents and I believe he is not guilty.

Given it had been closed twice, 
it was surprising that the Swedish investigation was opened a third time.  
In Sweden the decision was met with surprise-
the head of the Swedish bar association said it should be closed once and for all.
If you read his statement to the Swedish prosecutor, you learn a lot about so many irregularities in this case https://t.co/8mFNTEHK1l
https://t.co/kEtRQLM3Sd

When there was a 120-man Pentagon task force in operation.  Weeks after the release of the Afghan and Iraq War logs was published.  
When the US knew Julian had 251,000 diplomati cables that he intended to publish.

The timing of the case being resurrected the first time - 
by another prosecutor in another jurisdiction - 
was a month before a Swedish election.

The senior prosecutor, Eva Finne, had dropped the investigation 
not because she didn’t believe the women—
she did—
but because she said that from the alleged conduct there was no indication of criminality.
Back in 2010, Julian stayed in Sweden to be questioned by the prosecutor and after waiting around for 5 weeks, requested permission to leave which was granted.

It took the prosecutor six years to carry out her job to conduct an initial interview with him. 
You don’t have to be an expert to know that in these kinds of cases, you need to interview the person as close as possible to the alleged events.

So 
the procedural violations alone make it impossible for Julian to face a fair proceeding

It has exposed a man 
who has at no point been charged to unnecessary suspicion. 
The Swedish authorities have almost run out the clock, it’s taken them nine years and they still have an open ‘preliminary investigation’, without deciding whether they want to press charges or not

The way the Swedish investigation has been conducted has been repeatedly condemned - 
by the UN working group on arbitrary detention, 
by the Swedish appeal court, 
and by the UN Special Rapporteur on torture, among others.
Julian sought asylum from the very scenario he now faces: extradition to a US show trial, facing 175 years in jail, an effective death sentence, all for publishing information in the public interest.
Julian sought and Ecuador gave asylum because of the credible threat of US prosecution for publishing. No country on earth gives asylum to a non-citizen to avoid sexual misconduct allegations.

For so many years, 
we heard that Julian was in the Ecuadorian Embassy to avoid the allegations in Sweden. 
This was never the case.
